# What We've Done, What Remains

*Fourteenth paper in the Concordius series, and the close of Section II. It introduces nothing new. It gathers what the foregoing papers established, and states the one thing they could not.*

---

## Abstract

This paper summarizes Section II. Where Section I built the architecture, Section II put it to work — deriving the limit the structure cannot pass, the measure it answers that limit with, the two laws by which any created process moves, the method by which those laws are read off a made thing, and three demonstrations that the method holds across poetry, music, and the visible and bodily form. It closes by being exact about the boundary of all this. Every operation in the section was performed on the structure itself, from inside it: the same H₄₈ substrate, examined, measured, and read. What none of it has yet done is turn outward — to the long record of what has actually been made, and made over time. The section ends having learned to read, and not yet having read the world.

